  "prompt": "What causes an invalid pregnancy test?",
  "response": "An invalid pregnancy test result means the test didn't work properly, and you can't rely on the result displayed.  There are several reasons why this can happen:\n\n*   **Insufficient Urine:** Not enough urine applied to the test strip is a common cause.  Make sure you saturate the absorbent tip thoroughly, following the instructions.\n\n*   **Applying Urine to the Wrong Part of the Test:** Each test has a specific area designed to absorb the urine. If you apply urine to the wrong part, the test won't work correctly.\n\n*   **Too Much Urine:**  Over-saturating the test can also interfere with the chemical reactions.\n\n*   **Timing Issues:**\n    *   **Reading the Results Too Early:** Some tests require a specific waiting time (usually 3-5 minutes) for the reaction to occur. Reading the result before the specified time can lead to an invalid result.\n    *   **Reading the Results Too Late:** After a certain time (usually 10-15 minutes, check the instructions), the test result may no longer be accurate and can produce an evaporation line that looks like a faint positive or an invalid result.\n\n*   **Expired or Damaged Test:** Using an expired test or one that has been damaged (e.g., exposed to moisture) can lead to inaccurate or invalid results. Check the expiration date and ensure the test packaging is intact.\n\n*   **Faulty Test:** Occasionally, a test may be defective due to manufacturing errors.\n\n*   **Test Not Stored Properly:**  Improper storage, like exposure to extreme temperatures or humidity, can damage the test and affect its accuracy.\n\n*   **Interfering Substances (Rare):** While rare, certain substances or conditions could potentially interfere with the test, though this is uncommon with modern tests. These might include certain rare medical conditions or very high levels of protein in the urine.\n\n**What to do if you get an invalid result:**\n\n1.  **Read the Instructions Again:**  Make sure you followed the instructions exactly.\n2.  **Try Again:**  Wait a few days and retest using a new test. First-morning urine is usually recommended because it's the most concentrated.\n3.  **Consider a Different Test:** If you continue to get invalid results, try a different brand of pregnancy test.\n4.  **Consult a Doctor:** The most reliable way to confirm or rule out pregnancy is to see a doctor for a blood test. Blood tests are more sensitive and accurate than home urine tests. They can also detect pregnancy earlier.\n\nIt's important not to assume you are or aren't pregnant based on an invalid test result. Retesting or seeking medical advice is crucial.\n",
